          "body": "Verses 8-11 are the psalm's cosmic expansion. The vision moves from specific petition for Israel's afflicted (vv. 1-7) to the ends of the earth (v. 8), from desert nomads to the kings of Tarshish and Sheba (vv. 9-10), from Israel's people (v. 2) to all nations (v. 11). The geographic movement is the Abrahamic promise scaled to royal dimensions. Solomon's historical reign came closest to this — 1 Kings 4:21 records that 'Solomon ruled over all the kingdoms from the River to the land of the Philistines and to the border of Egypt,' and the Queen of Sheba brought gold and spices (1 Kings 10:1-10), echoing vv. 10, 15 almost exactly. But Solomon's reign was neither permanent nor universal, and his kingdom fractured immediately after his death. The gap between the prayer and any historical fulfillment is the psalm's messianic opening: it prays for what no Davidic king could sustain, pointing toward the One of whom Revelation 11:15 says, 'The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of His Christ, and He will reign forever and ever.'"
