          "body": "Verse 6's image is one of the most beautiful in the royal psalms: 'May he come down like rain upon the mown grass, like showers that water the earth.' Mown grass is cut grass, already shorn and exposed — in the ancient Near East, a field of cut grass under the scorching Palestinian sun would quickly die without rain. The image is of vulnerability met by life-giving provision. The king's reign refreshes, restores, and enables growth in those who have been cut down. This is not power for power's sake; it is power deployed as care. The agricultural extension in v. 16 — grain waving on mountaintops like the cedars of Lebanon — points in the same direction: the ideal king's reign reverses barrenness and produces extravagant abundance even in places that naturally cannot sustain it. The imagery draws on the creation blessing of Genesis 1-2 and anticipates the new-creation abundance of Revelation 22:1-2. Righteous rule produces flourishing; the land itself responds to justice."
