        "excerpt": "For he will deliver the needy when he cries for help, the afflicted also, and him who has no helper.",
        "body": "The particle 'for' (ki) in v. 12 is the psalm's theological spine. The universal dominion just described (vv. 8-11) is now grounded in the king's compassionate justice. All nations bow before him not because he is militarily irresistible but because he is the kind of king who delivers the helpless. The logic is striking: the most powerful king in history is the one who cares most for the weakest. This inverts every ancient Near Eastern model of power.\n\nThe progression of v. 12's portrait is carefully constructed. The needy 'cries for help' (shava) — not a dignified petition but a desperate cry, the same vocabulary used of Israel crying to God in Egypt (Exodus 2:23). This king hears that cry and delivers. The afflicted (ani, again) have no human helper (ozer ayin — helper absent); their only hope is the king who functions as the divine-human bridge, embodying in royal form the God of Psalm 68:5 who is 'a father of the fatherless and a judge for the widows.' Verse 14 is the psalm's ethical apex: 'their blood will be precious in his sight.' The blood (dam) of the poor — their very lives — is valued by the king as something of high worth, not to be spilled carelessly, not to be traded for political convenience.\n\nThis section has direct christological import. When Jesus reads Isaiah 61:1-2 in the Nazareth synagogue ('The Spirit of the Lord is upon Me to preach the gospel to the poor... to proclaim release to the captives,' Luke 4:18-19), he is claiming the mantle of the ideal king of Psalm 72. When he says 'blessed are the poor in spirit' and 'blessed are those who mourn' (Matthew 5:3-4), the king who delivers the needy with no helper has arrived. The precious blood of Psalm 72:14 — the king's valuation of the poor's lives — will reach its climax when the King's own blood is poured out to redeem theirs (1 Peter 1:18-19).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ki* (for, v. 12) — causal conjunction; this is the theological hinge. *Shava* (cries for help) — to cry out urgently; the root of the Hebrew word for salvation (*yeshua*). *Yaqar* (precious, v. 14) — costly, of great value; used of precious stones, of wisdom (Proverbs 3:15), and of the life of the anointed king (1 Samuel 26:21). *Gaal* (redeem, v. 14) — the kinsman-redeemer term; the king acts as go'el for the helpless."
